Data Cleaning and processing

Data cleaning

# Drop token (useless col)
Token <- RecordDF_A$token
RecordDF_A<-RecordDF_A[-c(1)]

RecordDF_A <- na.omit(RecordDF_A)

Train-test spliting

# Train test split
DataSize=nrow(RecordDF_A) ## how many rows?
TrainingSet_Size<-floor(DataSize*(3/4)) ## Size for training set
TestSet_Size <- DataSize - TrainingSet_Size ## Size for testing set

set.seed(123)
MyTrainSample <- sample(nrow(RecordDF_A),
                                    TrainingSet_Size,replace=FALSE)

# training data
MyTrainingSET <- RecordDF_A[MyTrainSample,]
# table(MyTrainingSET$Quotes_label)

# true label of train data
TrainKnownLabels <- MyTrainingSET$Quotes_label
MyTrainingSET <- MyTrainingSET[ , -which(names(MyTrainingSET) %in% c("Quotes_label"))]

# testing data
MyTestSET <- RecordDF_A[-MyTrainSample,]
# table(MyTestSET$Quotes_label)

# true label of test data
TestKnownLabels <- MyTestSET$Quotes_label
MyTestSET <- MyTestSET[ , -which(names(MyTestSET) %in% c("Quotes_label"))]

Data normalization

meltData <- melt(MyTrainingSET[1:(ncol(MyTrainingSET)-4)],ignore_index = FALSE)
## Using  as id variables
boxplot(data=meltData, value~variable)

Navie Bayes

Model training

train_x = MyTrainingSET
train_y = TrainKnownLabels

control <- trainControl(method = "cv",number = 5)

nb_ori <- train(
    x = train_x,
    y = train_y,
    method = "nb",
    trControl = control
)

Confusion Matrix

Predict <- predict(nb_ori,MyTestSET)
table(Predict,TestKnownLabels)
##                TestKnownLabels
## Predict         High position Low position Middle
##   High position            10            2      1
##   Low position              2            7      5
##   Middle                    1            6      9
heatmap(table(Predict,TestKnownLabels))

Important features

X <- varImp(nb_ori, scale = FALSE)
plot(X)

Tuning parameters

para <- expand.grid(usekernel = c(TRUE, FALSE),fL = 0:7, adjust = seq(0, 7, by = 1))

nb.m2 <- train(
    x = train_x,
    y = train_y,
    method = "nb",
    trControl = control,
    tuneGrid = para
)
ggplot(nb.m2) + 
  geom_line()+
  labs(title = "Parameter tunning")

Discussion

Naive Bayes is a classification technique based on Bayes’ Theorem with an assumption of independence among predictors. Compared with that algorithm in Python, R support a mixed data type while applying this model.

The confusion matrix performs not as well as it should be. The model seems to be more sensitive to recognizing “High position” price where this is much more similar to the result of “Decision Tree”. However, the predicting accuracy on another two classes performs not well, where it just achieved nearly half right classification.

In the tuning parameters stage, the overall accuracy under the cross-validation only achieves about 57% accuracy. It is clear that when “Laplace” goes around 1 to 2, the model will achieve its currently best performance.

Conclusion

  1. Top features include “bollinger band”, “DEMA” and the unless feature includes “ADX” and “APO”. This conclusion is conformed to the result of the “Decision Tree”
  2. Naive Bayes performs well in recognizing the “High position’ but is nearly random in predicting another two classes.

SVM

“Poly” kernel

MyTrainingSET <- MyTrainingSET[1:(ncol(MyTrainingSET)-4)]
MyTrainingSET$Label <- TrainKnownLabels

MyTestSET <- MyTestSET[1:(ncol(MyTestSET)-4)]
# Polynomial Kernel
SVM_fit_P <- svm(Label~.,data = MyTrainingSET,
                 kernel="polynomial", cost=.1, 
                 scale=FALSE)

                   kernel="polynomial",

Discussion

The confusion matrix shows that the SVM with “poly” kernel did not useful because all the predictions are concentrated in “Low position”. One of the possible explanation could be that, the “poly” kernel create biase on the “low position”, and this may need a deeper research on what happen to the “poly” kernel.

Compared with the “poly” kernel, the “linear” kernel improved a lot in recognizing the “High position” and “middle”. One possible reason for this improvement could come from the linear separable. This linear separability help reduce some bias compared with the mode with the “ploy” kernel.

Discussion

Similar to the mode with the “poly” kernel, there is the same bias with the “Radial” kernel.

Conclusion

  1. Compared with the Naive Bayes, SVM’s performance performs worse no matter which kernel is chosen.
  2. As a supervised and math-supported method in machine learning, Support vector machines (SVMs) did not achieve a reasonable prediction. One guessed reason is that since SVM is preferred the linear separable dataset. However, the dataset in this project is mostly not linearly separable.
  3. The bad prediction of SVM implied a fact that the utility of financial indicators should be reconsidered before it is used for trading.
